MIKE PROCOPIO: All right.

00:00:09.230 --> 00:00:11.320
Well, good afternoon everybody,
and welcome to

00:00:11.320 --> 00:00:14.120
Google I/O. We are grateful
to have you here.

00:00:14.120 --> 00:00:15.430
My name is Mike Procopio.

00:00:15.430 --> 00:00:18.180
I'm a software engineer on the
Google Drive SDK team.

00:00:18.180 --> 00:00:19.690
STEVEN BAZYL: And I'm
Steven Bazyl.

00:00:19.690 --> 00:00:22.665
I'm a developer advocate also
working on the SDK.

00:00:22.665 --> 00:00:25.220
MIKE PROCOPIO: And today Steve
and I are going to help you

00:00:25.220 --> 00:00:27.430
make your apps rock.

00:00:27.430 --> 00:00:27.890
OK.

00:00:27.890 --> 00:00:31.550
So we are here to talk
about Google Drive.

00:00:31.550 --> 00:00:34.130
So Google Drive is the place
where you can store your files

00:00:34.130 --> 00:00:35.680
securely in the cloud.

00:00:35.680 --> 00:00:38.200
You also get for free the
fundamentals of Google Drive--

00:00:38.200 --> 00:00:42.380
sharing, searching,
collaboration, file revisions,

00:00:42.380 --> 00:00:45.440
organization, and even neat
little features like uploading

00:00:45.440 --> 00:00:47.210
an image and it will
automatically do

00:00:47.210 --> 00:00:49.320
identification of what's in
that image and make it

00:00:49.320 --> 00:00:49.820
searchable.

00:00:49.820 --> 00:00:51.600
All that comes for free.

00:00:51.600 --> 00:00:55.100
With the Sync client, the Sync
program, you can keep files in

00:00:55.100 --> 00:00:57.510
sync from your local hard drive
on your machine back

00:00:57.510 --> 00:01:00.610
home with files in the cloud,
and the changes will propagate

00:01:00.610 --> 00:01:01.760
as expected.

00:01:01.760 --> 00:01:05.840
And of course, one of the key
benefits of files in the cloud

00:01:05.840 --> 00:01:08.680
is that you can access
them from anywhere.

00:01:08.680 --> 00:01:13.340
So where are we today, a
snapshot with Google Drive.

00:01:13.340 --> 00:01:16.350
Millions of users have
opted into Drive.

00:01:16.350 --> 00:01:18.610
There are more juicy stats,
but that's what we

00:01:18.610 --> 00:01:20.050
can say right now.

00:01:20.050 --> 00:01:23.620
And we have fully realized the
idea of access anywhere, so

00:01:23.620 --> 00:01:26.460
that means on the web, but
also on mobile devices of

00:01:26.460 --> 00:01:30.110
various flavors and
using Chrome OS.

00:01:30.110 --> 00:01:33.060
We have an easy to use, fully
featured SDK software

00:01:33.060 --> 00:01:35.500
development kit, with client
library support in eight

00:01:35.500 --> 00:01:38.380
languages, the second version
of which we just announced

00:01:38.380 --> 00:01:39.230
this morning--

00:01:39.230 --> 00:01:40.800
really excited about that.

00:01:40.800 --> 00:01:43.590
And a snapshot right now in the
Chrome Web Store, which is

00:01:43.590 --> 00:01:47.240
where we go to find apps, we
have 50 third-party drive apps

00:01:47.240 --> 00:01:49.090
available right now in
the Chrome Web Store.

00:01:49.090 --> 00:01:52.270
STEVEN BAZYL: Yeah, I think we
just added Objective-C and

00:01:52.270 --> 00:01:55.960
JavaScript today, in addition to
Java, Python, Ruby, and all

00:01:55.960 --> 00:01:56.370
those other guys.

00:01:56.370 --> 00:01:57.330
MIKE PROCOPIO: Absolutely.

00:01:57.330 --> 00:02:00.230
So, two more since V1 of launch,
since the version one

00:02:00.230 --> 00:02:01.970
of the SDK.

00:02:01.970 --> 00:02:03.670
Pretty thrilled about that.

00:02:03.670 --> 00:02:05.370
So, a pretty good foundation.

00:02:05.370 --> 00:02:06.860
So what's next?

00:02:06.860 --> 00:02:09.720
Well, the answer is you, and our
apps, and the things that

00:02:09.720 --> 00:02:10.900
we can do together.

00:02:10.900 --> 00:02:13.700
That's what's next, because
right now on Google Drive we

00:02:13.700 --> 00:02:16.880
have a pretty solid set of
built-in applications, first

00:02:16.880 --> 00:02:20.690
class productivity apps that
offer real time collaboration,

00:02:20.690 --> 00:02:22.510
sharing all the things
that come with Drive.

00:02:22.510 --> 00:02:24.890
We have a word processor,
Google Documents,

00:02:24.890 --> 00:02:28.400
Presentation, Spreadsheets,
and Drawings, the four

00:02:28.400 --> 00:02:32.020
fundamental types that we have
right now today in Drive.

00:02:32.020 --> 00:02:34.440
We also have the built-in Google
Drive Viewer, which

00:02:34.440 --> 00:02:37.640
gives you a static preview
experience for lots of

00:02:37.640 --> 00:02:38.940
different file types.

00:02:38.940 --> 00:02:42.280
So basic things like PDFs and
images, videos and text, we

00:02:42.280 --> 00:02:44.090
can render a pretty good
static preview.

00:02:44.090 --> 00:02:45.770
Right here, you want
to check this out?

00:02:45.770 --> 00:02:47.000
Here, have a look.

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:49.890
And we also have support for a
few proprietary formats like

00:02:49.890 --> 00:02:53.470
Photoshop, Illustrator, and even
Microsoft Office formats.

00:02:53.470 --> 00:02:58.300
So that's pretty great, but
it's basic preview only--

00:02:58.300 --> 00:03:00.320
you can't do anything with it.

00:03:00.320 --> 00:03:05.790
So here's an example of what you
can do right now with the

00:03:05.790 --> 00:03:07.860
Google Drive Viewer on
a file type in Drive.

00:03:07.860 --> 00:03:09.800
You can read your scintillating
scientific

00:03:09.800 --> 00:03:12.400
publications that you keep in
Drive to remind yourself of

00:03:12.400 --> 00:03:12.890
how exciting--

00:03:12.890 --> 00:03:13.190
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:03:13.190 --> 00:03:15.450
STEVEN BAZYL: And that is
actually your paper?

00:03:15.450 --> 00:03:18.550
MIKE PROCOPIO: I don't think
I noticed that before.

00:03:18.550 --> 00:03:21.030
It might be that one time
when I was a roboticist.

00:03:21.030 --> 00:03:22.450
That's that.

00:03:22.450 --> 00:03:25.430
I reread it every now and then,
and man, that's boring.

00:03:25.430 --> 00:03:26.380
OK.

00:03:26.380 --> 00:03:29.810
So you can also-- more static
preview, preview photos of the

00:03:29.810 --> 00:03:33.230
places you wish you were
on vacation to.

00:03:33.230 --> 00:03:35.840
And then, of course, video
experience is very prominently

00:03:35.840 --> 00:03:37.400
represented in Drive.

00:03:37.400 --> 00:03:41.700
You can watch the video of you
getting second place in a 5K

00:03:41.700 --> 00:03:44.830
race over and over again, not
because you're bitter or

00:03:44.830 --> 00:03:48.920
anything, but that's just
what you can do.

00:03:48.920 --> 00:03:50.970
However, the built-in
apps in that file

00:03:50.970 --> 00:03:52.670
preview, it's just a start.

00:03:52.670 --> 00:03:54.230
It's just a starting place.

00:03:54.230 --> 00:03:56.590
As an ecosystem together,
we can definitely

00:03:56.590 --> 00:03:57.970
do better for sure.

00:03:57.970 --> 00:04:00.340
So here's a snapshot of apps
right now that are already in

00:04:00.340 --> 00:04:01.170
the ecosystem.

00:04:01.170 --> 00:04:03.440
Steve's been working with a
lot of these partners, and

00:04:03.440 --> 00:04:05.030
this is where we've landed.

00:04:05.030 --> 00:04:06.670
More on that here in a second.

00:04:06.670 --> 00:04:09.130
So if you take away the static
preview constraint and

00:04:09.130 --> 00:04:12.090
actually started to embrace
third party apps in Drive--

00:04:12.090 --> 00:04:14.740
completely cloud enabled
access anywhere--

00:04:14.740 --> 00:04:17.220
these are the sorts of
experiences that you can have.

00:04:17.220 --> 00:04:19.209
So HelloFax is an application
that we have right

00:04:19.209 --> 00:04:21.510
now in the Web Store.

00:04:21.510 --> 00:04:23.150
You can do something
useful with a PDF.

00:04:23.150 --> 00:04:26.870
You can fax it for later offline
consumption when your

00:04:26.870 --> 00:04:28.820
Wi-Fi goes down.

00:04:28.820 --> 00:04:31.220
You can also do things like
an e-reader could

00:04:31.220 --> 00:04:32.180
operate on a PDF.

00:04:32.180 --> 00:04:33.840
There's lots of use
cases here.

00:04:33.840 --> 00:04:37.230
Another example is another app
that we partner with, Pixlr

00:04:37.230 --> 00:04:41.110
Image Editor, a pretty robust
compelling first class image

00:04:41.110 --> 00:04:43.990
editing app that works
on the Web.

00:04:43.990 --> 00:04:45.910
And so you can give your
photos that kind of hip

00:04:45.910 --> 00:04:48.380
vintage look that all the cool
kids are doing these days, and

00:04:48.380 --> 00:04:50.760
instantly thereby boosting
your social

00:04:50.760 --> 00:04:51.620
network street cred.

00:04:51.620 --> 00:04:53.805
STEVEN BAZYL: And then share
them on Google+.

00:04:53.805 --> 00:04:56.350
MIKE PROCOPIO: Exactly, and
share it on Google+, these hip

00:04:56.350 --> 00:04:57.180
new photos.

00:04:57.180 --> 00:04:59.840
But, of course, really we know
how you're going to use this,

00:04:59.840 --> 00:05:03.470
and that is to create lolcat
memes early and often.

00:05:03.470 --> 00:05:05.590
So that's what I use that for.

00:05:05.590 --> 00:05:08.440
And, of course, with the video
experience, when you bring it

00:05:08.440 --> 00:05:09.900
into the cloud with third-party
apps, you can do

00:05:09.900 --> 00:05:11.180
more than just preview it.

00:05:11.180 --> 00:05:13.730
You can actually edit it now, so
your friends don't need to

00:05:13.730 --> 00:05:17.660
know that you got second place
in a race by one second.

00:05:17.660 --> 00:05:20.430
You can edit it, and surely this
guy here looks like he's

00:05:20.430 --> 00:05:21.450
winning the race.

00:05:21.450 --> 00:05:22.640
We'll see about that.

00:05:22.640 --> 00:05:26.140
So apps bring life
to our ecosystem.

00:05:26.140 --> 00:05:29.790
So with apps, you can fax and
edit, render, graph, and draw

00:05:29.790 --> 00:05:32.590
diagrams, sign and publish,
map, chart,

00:05:32.590 --> 00:05:34.130
listen, mock and plan.

00:05:34.130 --> 00:05:37.130
And you can do this all
right now, today, with

00:05:37.130 --> 00:05:39.430
Google Drive apps.

00:05:39.430 --> 00:05:41.650
And when you build a Google
Drive app, one of the key

00:05:41.650 --> 00:05:45.510
values that our SDK lets you
bring to your users is to

00:05:45.510 --> 00:05:49.300
integrate deeply with the Google
Drive web UI, mobile

00:05:49.300 --> 00:05:50.690
and web clients.

00:05:50.690 --> 00:05:53.530
And so this means that we
give apps a first class

00:05:53.530 --> 00:05:57.000
representation in Google Drive,
from management and

00:05:57.000 --> 00:05:59.950
viewing product details,
searching by things created

00:05:59.950 --> 00:06:03.210
with the app, as well as the
ability to create new using

00:06:03.210 --> 00:06:06.050
your apps, so a launcher kind
of state, and of course, the

00:06:06.050 --> 00:06:09.490
ability to open with using your
app for the things that

00:06:09.490 --> 00:06:10.600
it has registered for.

00:06:10.600 --> 00:06:12.960
So you can use HelloFax
to open with

00:06:12.960 --> 00:06:15.210
on a PDF, for example.

00:06:15.210 --> 00:06:19.010
So Steve and I are here to help
you continue to use this

00:06:19.010 --> 00:06:21.980
SDK and to build awesome apps.

00:06:21.980 --> 00:06:24.230
These are vibrant and polished
apps that are first and

00:06:24.230 --> 00:06:28.210
foremost secure, they put the
user first, and they integrate

00:06:28.210 --> 00:06:29.870
well with Google Drive.

00:06:29.870 --> 00:06:31.990
So let's take a quick look at
nine things that we can do

00:06:31.990 --> 00:06:34.670
right now to get your apps
to this polished state.

00:06:34.670 --> 00:06:39.670
STEVEN BAZYL: And I'm going to
take the first one, which is

00:06:39.670 --> 00:06:41.270
just to talk about UX.

00:06:41.270 --> 00:06:45.340
And this is really going to be
geared towards apps that are

00:06:45.340 --> 00:06:47.000
document oriented.

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:50.890
You're building a photo editor,
a charting tool,

00:06:50.890 --> 00:06:53.700
anything like that-- something
that fits really well within

00:06:53.700 --> 00:06:57.420
that Google Docs ecosystem.

00:06:57.420 --> 00:06:58.740
And I love this quote.

00:06:58.740 --> 00:07:01.310
This is probably one of the most
probably misunderstood

00:07:01.310 --> 00:07:04.810
and abused quotes among software
developers, at least

00:07:04.810 --> 00:07:06.660
in my history.

00:07:06.660 --> 00:07:08.930
Whenever we talk about design
patterns or conventions or

00:07:08.930 --> 00:07:11.520
anything, somebody inevitably
will bring this up and say,

00:07:11.520 --> 00:07:13.280
oh, consistency it's
not important.

00:07:13.280 --> 00:07:15.320
That's only for stupid people.

00:07:15.320 --> 00:07:16.340
Not true at all.

00:07:16.340 --> 00:07:17.540
It's a foolish consistency.

00:07:17.540 --> 00:07:21.370
It's when you're doing things
for no reason just because

00:07:21.370 --> 00:07:23.900
they're a convention that
it becomes a bad idea.

00:07:23.900 --> 00:07:28.500
But every platform, whether
it's Windows OS X, iOS,

00:07:28.500 --> 00:07:30.920
Android, they all have
conventions for a reason.

00:07:30.920 --> 00:07:33.573
It's because it makes the users
a lot more familiar and

00:07:33.573 --> 00:07:37.070
a lot more comfortable
with your apps.

00:07:37.070 --> 00:07:39.280
When you're not consistent,
bad things happen.

00:07:39.280 --> 00:07:41.390
So we actually did a
little UX study.

00:07:41.390 --> 00:07:43.590
This is when we were first
starting our trusted tester

00:07:43.590 --> 00:07:46.960
period for Drive apps, and some
of the apps we tried were

00:07:46.960 --> 00:07:49.360
little toy apps that
we built ourselves.

00:07:49.360 --> 00:07:52.570
Some were actually apps from
external developers.

00:07:52.570 --> 00:07:55.620
We put them in front of users
and asked them to do just

00:07:55.620 --> 00:07:57.690
really basic activities
with all these apps.

00:07:57.690 --> 00:07:59.770
And the problem was, because
there are so many

00:07:59.770 --> 00:08:04.290
inconsistencies in how people
did basic operations, most of

00:08:04.290 --> 00:08:07.090
the users-- in this case,
over 2/3 of them--

00:08:07.090 --> 00:08:08.160
just got lost.

00:08:08.160 --> 00:08:11.030
They didn't know how
to use those apps.

00:08:11.030 --> 00:08:13.130
So this is Google Docs.

00:08:13.130 --> 00:08:17.890
This is our word processing
tool, and it looks like any

00:08:17.890 --> 00:08:19.830
other word processing tool,
but there's a couple key

00:08:19.830 --> 00:08:24.375
elements I want to point out to
how the UI is put together.

00:08:24.375 --> 00:08:27.305
So we have some really basic
information about what file am

00:08:27.305 --> 00:08:28.520
I working on.

00:08:28.520 --> 00:08:31.220
Imagine a text editor that
didn't tell you the file name

00:08:31.220 --> 00:08:32.110
that you were editing--

00:08:32.110 --> 00:08:34.320
it wouldn't be very useful.

00:08:34.320 --> 00:08:36.679
Likewise, a lot of us use
multiple accounts, so it's

00:08:36.679 --> 00:08:40.270
really helpful to know which
account we're locked in with.

00:08:40.270 --> 00:08:41.200
Obviously, content--

00:08:41.200 --> 00:08:42.470
that's the point of the app.

00:08:42.470 --> 00:08:43.659
That's your section,
you really want

00:08:43.659 --> 00:08:45.930
to make this great.

00:08:45.930 --> 00:08:48.750
Navigation is always nice and
consistent up in that basic

00:08:48.750 --> 00:08:49.390
menu structure.

00:08:49.390 --> 00:08:51.990
And, of course, we have our
collaboration and sharing.

00:08:51.990 --> 00:08:54.710
The cool thing is with Docs is
that I can switch over to any

00:08:54.710 --> 00:08:57.440
of the other tools that Mike
talked about earlier, those

00:08:57.440 --> 00:08:59.760
presentations or spreadsheets,
and I'm going to have the

00:08:59.760 --> 00:09:03.200
exact same layout for all
of those applications.

00:09:03.200 --> 00:09:05.670
And from a user's perspective,
that's awesome, right?

00:09:05.670 --> 00:09:08.840
I can switch to one of these
apps, and be productive almost

00:09:08.840 --> 00:09:11.030
immediately.

00:09:11.030 --> 00:09:12.630
So I want to show a third
party application.

00:09:12.630 --> 00:09:16.020
This is Lucidchart, and I think
they did a really great

00:09:16.020 --> 00:09:19.980
job at balancing between having
their own distinct look

00:09:19.980 --> 00:09:24.880
and feel and using those
conventions that help users be

00:09:24.880 --> 00:09:27.840
really productive and feel
familiar with the application.

00:09:27.840 --> 00:09:32.335
Lucidchart is a collaborative
charting tool, where you could

00:09:32.335 --> 00:09:36.910
do flowcharts, spin diagrams,
mockups for different UIs.

00:09:36.910 --> 00:09:38.600
We're just going to
launch this here.

00:09:38.600 --> 00:09:43.710
And it just takes a couple
seconds to load up, but I'm

00:09:43.710 --> 00:09:52.420
going to create a new document,
and we're not going

00:09:52.420 --> 00:09:53.040
to give it a title.

00:09:53.040 --> 00:09:55.830
But basically, you see here this
actually looks a lot like

00:09:55.830 --> 00:09:57.250
any of the Google
Docs editors.

00:09:57.250 --> 00:10:00.070
We have the same elements we had
here before-- our document

00:10:00.070 --> 00:10:02.950
title, our file menu, our
sharing and account

00:10:02.950 --> 00:10:06.140
information, a huge content
section, but it still is

00:10:06.140 --> 00:10:07.770
distinctly their app.

00:10:07.770 --> 00:10:10.355
So for building applications
that are really geared at

00:10:10.355 --> 00:10:14.740
being productivity apps that are
meant to be complimentary

00:10:14.740 --> 00:10:19.330
tools to the basic office type
applications, try to use these

00:10:19.330 --> 00:10:23.120
consistencies, try to follow
these conventions much as if

00:10:23.120 --> 00:10:26.730
you're building an app for a
mobile platform or one of the

00:10:26.730 --> 00:10:27.980
desktop environments.

00:10:30.090 --> 00:10:35.200
Let me switch back to the
presentation here for you.

00:10:35.200 --> 00:10:36.530
Ooh, that was bad.

00:10:39.270 --> 00:10:41.990
All right, there we go.

00:10:41.990 --> 00:10:42.860
MIKE PROCOPIO: All right.

00:10:42.860 --> 00:10:44.110
Thanks, Steve.

00:10:44.110 --> 00:10:46.460
So one of the key value
propositions of Google Drive

00:10:46.460 --> 00:10:49.010
is that you can access
your stuff anywhere.

00:10:49.010 --> 00:10:51.160
Drive is fully enabled
in mobile context.

00:10:51.160 --> 00:10:53.020
This is something that's
very important to us.

00:10:53.020 --> 00:10:55.630
So one of the things that your
app can do to be particularly

00:10:55.630 --> 00:10:58.670
polished is also work well in
a mobile context, which is

00:10:58.670 --> 00:11:01.120
becoming increasingly
how we work.

00:11:01.120 --> 00:11:04.690
And so by mobile context, we
don't mean just phones but

00:11:04.690 --> 00:11:06.550
tablets as well--

00:11:06.550 --> 00:11:08.190
a very exciting announcement
today.

00:11:08.190 --> 00:11:10.260
And then Chrome OS just
recently-- we'd like to

00:11:10.260 --> 00:11:14.070
announce that Chrome OS
has full Drive SDK

00:11:14.070 --> 00:11:15.350
integration as well.

00:11:15.350 --> 00:11:17.540
So here's an example of
something that works

00:11:17.540 --> 00:11:18.960
today, right now.

00:11:18.960 --> 00:11:22.470
So an application doesn't
necessarily have to build a

00:11:22.470 --> 00:11:25.190
native app to have a
mobile experience.

00:11:25.190 --> 00:11:27.990
So in this case, Aviary, which
is an image editor that's

00:11:27.990 --> 00:11:30.480
available right now in our Web
Store, you can do basic

00:11:30.480 --> 00:11:32.080
cropping, these sorts
of things.

00:11:32.080 --> 00:11:35.700
It actually is an HTML5 app
that works in the Web.

00:11:35.700 --> 00:11:38.610
So there is a native app, but
we don't need the native app

00:11:38.610 --> 00:11:40.860
