00:16:33.850 --> 00:16:36.445
So earlier in the talk, we
talked about how important it

00:16:36.445 --> 00:16:37.940
was that your app is secure.

00:16:37.940 --> 00:16:40.310
It's perhaps the most important
thing that we can do

00:16:40.310 --> 00:16:43.960
is to safeguard the user's data,
so we make this very

00:16:43.960 --> 00:16:45.250
easy to do.

00:16:45.250 --> 00:16:48.430
And the fundamental mechanism
for protecting the user's data

00:16:48.430 --> 00:16:51.870
is this notion of scopes, or
levels of access, that your

00:16:51.870 --> 00:16:55.480
application requests, the user
approves, and then is then

00:16:55.480 --> 00:16:56.820
granted to your application--

00:16:56.820 --> 00:16:59.540
for example, to access files
on the user's drive.

00:16:59.540 --> 00:17:02.560
So once upon a time, these
levels of access were kind of

00:17:02.560 --> 00:17:04.630
very coarse grained,
very broad.

00:17:04.630 --> 00:17:08.000
Things had access to entire
properties or websites.

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:11.900
So, for example, there is such
a scope, a security scope,

00:17:11.900 --> 00:17:14.530
that enables the application to
have access to the entire

00:17:14.530 --> 00:17:16.069
contents of the user's drive.

00:17:16.069 --> 00:17:19.500
Well, that seems pretty scary,
so what we've introduced as of

00:17:19.500 --> 00:17:22.109
Version One, and then we'll talk
about it pretty heavily

00:17:22.109 --> 00:17:25.960
here today, is this new scope
up here called drive.file.

00:17:25.960 --> 00:17:28.630
And this means that an
application has per file

00:17:28.630 --> 00:17:31.760
access to things on a one-off
basis based on user

00:17:31.760 --> 00:17:34.390
authorizations in your Drive.

00:17:34.390 --> 00:17:37.910
So let's take a look more
deeply about how

00:17:37.910 --> 00:17:41.050
this is going to work.

00:17:41.050 --> 00:17:41.930
Shupah!

00:17:41.930 --> 00:17:42.720
There we go.

00:17:42.720 --> 00:17:45.550
So this is a familiar sort
of consent page.

00:17:45.550 --> 00:17:47.740
On your Android devices, Android
has this built-in

00:17:47.740 --> 00:17:48.760
notion, as well.

00:17:48.760 --> 00:17:51.610
You approve native apps for
things' access on a more

00:17:51.610 --> 00:17:53.030
hardware system level--

00:17:53.030 --> 00:17:56.070
access to your location, access
to the contents of the

00:17:56.070 --> 00:17:58.310
secure digital card in your
phone, for example.

00:17:58.310 --> 00:17:58.670
OK.

00:17:58.670 --> 00:18:01.100
So the same notion applies
on the Web.

00:18:01.100 --> 00:18:03.880
And here for example, Balsamiq
Mockups, which is one of our

00:18:03.880 --> 00:18:06.230
partners, is requesting--

00:18:06.230 --> 00:18:08.760
and it's up to the
user to approve--

00:18:08.760 --> 00:18:10.040
information about your account,

00:18:10.040 --> 00:18:11.620
and your email address.

00:18:11.620 --> 00:18:15.810
And then here is perhaps the
most important request, here,

00:18:15.810 --> 00:18:18.400
is this view and manage Google
Drive files that you have

00:18:18.400 --> 00:18:20.310
opened or created
with this app.

00:18:20.310 --> 00:18:22.880
So this means this app is not
requesting broad access to the

00:18:22.880 --> 00:18:25.130
contents in the user's
Drive, but rather on

00:18:25.130 --> 00:18:26.610
a one by one basis.

00:18:26.610 --> 00:18:29.850
So in particular when the user
grants this scope, the app is

00:18:29.850 --> 00:18:33.010
able to create files
in the Drive.

00:18:33.010 --> 00:18:36.790
Also, open files that it created
and have access to

00:18:36.790 --> 00:18:40.240
files that the user explicitly
granted.

00:18:40.240 --> 00:18:43.280
So let's take a look at how
this works, because we

00:18:43.280 --> 00:18:46.550
surfaced this notion pretty
prominently in the Google

00:18:46.550 --> 00:18:47.940
Drive web UI.

00:18:47.940 --> 00:18:51.263
For example, here is a picture
of a place that I wish I was

00:18:51.263 --> 00:18:52.930
at for vacation, as
it turns out.

00:18:52.930 --> 00:18:55.440
And if we click View Authorized
Apps, we will see

00:18:55.440 --> 00:18:57.930
that currently there is nothing,
despite having

00:18:57.930 --> 00:19:00.990
installed apps, that is able
to access that file.

00:19:00.990 --> 00:19:03.090
So here's all the apps I have
installed right now.

00:19:03.090 --> 00:19:04.410
OK, good.

00:19:04.410 --> 00:19:07.450
So what I can do right now is
open this with one of the apps

00:19:07.450 --> 00:19:08.100
that I have installed.

00:19:08.100 --> 00:19:10.620
In this case, we will
highlight--

00:19:10.620 --> 00:19:13.900
let's do PicMonkey, another
image editing app.

00:19:13.900 --> 00:19:15.460
And here's the consent page--

00:19:15.460 --> 00:19:18.220
fairly clear, basic information,
email address,

00:19:18.220 --> 00:19:22.200
and I can expand this to see,
hey, this thing isn't going to

00:19:22.200 --> 00:19:24.710
be able to access all the stuff
in my drive, but rather

00:19:24.710 --> 00:19:26.450
just the things that
I tell it to.

00:19:26.450 --> 00:19:30.200
So we're going to allow access
to that, and PicMonkey is

00:19:30.200 --> 00:19:32.060
going to launch.

00:19:32.060 --> 00:19:35.480
It takes a little bit of time
to first initialize, but the

00:19:35.480 --> 00:19:39.240
picture of Napoli, a city
in Italy, comes up.

00:19:39.240 --> 00:19:41.840
I can crop and rotate and
do all that good stuff.

00:19:41.840 --> 00:19:44.230
But if I come back right now
to Drive, I have just

00:19:44.230 --> 00:19:46.480
authorized that application
to that file.

00:19:46.480 --> 00:19:48.520
So if I view authorized
apps, we will see

00:19:48.520 --> 00:19:50.060
PicMonkey shows up there.

00:19:50.060 --> 00:19:53.590
That is the only app that is
able to access this file, and

00:19:53.590 --> 00:19:55.700
we want to be very transparent
about this.

00:19:55.700 --> 00:19:58.250
And if the user wishes at any
point in time, when they're

00:19:58.250 --> 00:20:03.550
done, they can simply revoke
it, and PicMonkey no longer

00:20:03.550 --> 00:20:07.740
has access to that file until
the user reauthorizes it.

00:20:07.740 --> 00:20:11.750
So I think that wraps up
the security section.

00:20:11.750 --> 00:20:14.230
There's a number of scopes
including read-only, and the

00:20:14.230 --> 00:20:16.510
general notion here is to
request as few permissions and

00:20:16.510 --> 00:20:20.040
as narrow scoping as possible
that's best for you, your app,

00:20:20.040 --> 00:20:21.845
and the user as well.

00:20:21.845 --> 00:20:23.095
STEVEN BAZYL: Cool.

