sharing things.

00:23:28.220 --> 00:23:31.690
So the same exact dialogue that
you see inside Drive,

00:23:31.690 --> 00:23:35.860
inside all of our editors, and
then I can just go in here and

00:23:35.860 --> 00:23:38.460
share this with--

00:23:38.460 --> 00:23:41.190
send it to my personal
account.

00:23:41.190 --> 00:23:45.630
And the same flow as if I shared
it from within Drive.

00:23:45.630 --> 00:23:50.740
The cool thing is the actual
work to implement this is

00:23:50.740 --> 00:23:53.880
pretty trivial.

00:23:53.880 --> 00:23:56.900
And the fact that they were able
to do this in about half

00:23:56.900 --> 00:23:59.560
an hour yesterday was
pretty awesome.

00:23:59.560 --> 00:24:01.940
So first thing we do, just like
we did with Picker, we

00:24:01.940 --> 00:24:02.870
have a loader script.

00:24:02.870 --> 00:24:04.020
It is a different one.

00:24:04.020 --> 00:24:06.230
So if you're using both, you
have two different loaders in

00:24:06.230 --> 00:24:09.940
there, but the rest of
it is very familiar.

00:24:09.940 --> 00:24:13.900
So we call this gapi.load,
load drive-share.

00:24:13.900 --> 00:24:16.860
Again, a callback for when that
library is loaded, and we

00:24:16.860 --> 00:24:19.205
want to show it in just
three lines of code.

00:24:19.205 --> 00:24:21.650
We build a share client
with our app ID.

00:24:21.650 --> 00:24:23.870
We say which items
we want to share.

00:24:23.870 --> 00:24:26.960
These do have to be items that
our app has access to, so they

00:24:26.960 --> 00:24:29.090
have to be things that we
created or that the user

00:24:29.090 --> 00:24:32.180
allows us to access, and then
we just show the dialog.

00:24:32.180 --> 00:24:34.970
Super, super simple, really
great way to add that sharing

00:24:34.970 --> 00:24:38.110
functionality into your app
with next to no effort

00:24:38.110 --> 00:24:40.158
whatsoever.

00:24:40.158 --> 00:24:41.620
MIKE PROCOPIO: Great.

00:24:41.620 --> 00:24:45.400
OK, so another short and sweet
kind of tip here is to be

00:24:45.400 --> 00:24:45.960
searchable.

00:24:45.960 --> 00:24:48.580
Google Drive lets you find your
content very easily and

00:24:48.580 --> 00:24:50.670
when you share your content with
other users, those users

00:24:50.670 --> 00:24:52.420
can find it easily as well.

00:24:52.420 --> 00:24:55.190
So for types that Google
knows about, we're

00:24:55.190 --> 00:24:56.590
able to index them.

00:24:56.590 --> 00:25:00.030
So Google Docs or a spreadsheet,
for example, has

00:25:00.030 --> 00:25:00.920
keywords in it.

00:25:00.920 --> 00:25:03.310
We index that automatically, and
when you search for that

00:25:03.310 --> 00:25:05.450
file, it pops up immediately.

00:25:05.450 --> 00:25:07.740
Well, it would be great to do
that for third-party apps, and

00:25:07.740 --> 00:25:09.250
this is something very important
to us, so we

00:25:09.250 --> 00:25:12.510
actually let third-party apps
specify every they save or

00:25:12.510 --> 00:25:13.810
update a file.

00:25:13.810 --> 00:25:16.340
Indexable text is basically a
list the keywords that the

00:25:16.340 --> 00:25:19.310
user can use to find your file,
because we certainly

00:25:19.310 --> 00:25:22.070
aren't able to decode all the
data models and the custom

00:25:22.070 --> 00:25:24.170
file formats that third-party
apps are sending you.

00:25:24.170 --> 00:25:27.960
So here is a short and
sweet quick demo.

00:25:27.960 --> 00:25:32.380
Some say, I've been told, that
I have a propensity to use

00:25:32.380 --> 00:25:37.050
kind of exciting large words,
like phenomenal, spectacular,

00:25:37.050 --> 00:25:39.290
fantastic, and marvelous.

00:25:39.290 --> 00:25:40.120
It is true--

00:25:40.120 --> 00:25:42.490
I actually keep a map of them
with a third-party app called

00:25:42.490 --> 00:25:45.170
MindMeister, but I don't
know where that is.

00:25:45.170 --> 00:25:48.000
It's not showing up
in here anywhere.

00:25:48.000 --> 00:25:51.860
So let's search for a
word called stellar.

00:25:51.860 --> 00:25:52.540
There it is.

00:25:52.540 --> 00:25:55.600
So this is my map that I keep
of all these exciting words,

00:25:55.600 --> 00:25:57.900
so every time I need to use
one, to sound particularly

00:25:57.900 --> 00:26:00.900
important, I can just pull it
right off of this map and I

00:26:00.900 --> 00:26:03.930
have various synonyms that I
need on an as-needed basis.

00:26:03.930 --> 00:26:05.530
So, here-- spectacular,

00:26:05.530 --> 00:26:07.490
extraordinary, marvelous covered.

00:26:07.490 --> 00:26:10.510
So because MindMeister sets
indexable text, every time

00:26:10.510 --> 00:26:11.640
they save the file--

00:26:11.640 --> 00:26:12.950
which we know nothing about--

00:26:12.950 --> 00:26:16.950
we are able to search for that
and discover it very easily in

00:26:16.950 --> 00:26:18.850
the Drive UI as needed.

00:26:23.909 --> 00:26:25.352
You're good at that.

00:26:25.352 --> 00:26:26.360
STEVEN BAZYL: Tab tab.

00:26:26.360 --> 00:26:27.310
That's all I've got to do.

00:26:27.310 --> 00:26:28.995
MIKE PROCOPIO: All right,
another backup.

00:26:28.995 --> 00:26:31.695
STEVEN BAZYL: You have no faith
in the network, do you?

00:26:31.695 --> 00:26:32.320
MIKE PROCOPIO: No.

00:26:32.320 --> 00:26:35.770
STEVEN BAZYL: For someone who's
building cloud storage,

00:26:35.770 --> 00:26:37.875
you would expect a little
bit more confidence.

00:26:37.875 --> 00:26:39.125
MIKE PROCOPIO: Sorry.

00:26:41.230 --> 00:26:41.940
STEVEN BAZYL: All right.

00:26:41.940 --> 00:26:47.500
So this is another behavioral
thing with apps, and also

00:26:47.500 --> 00:26:50.180
something we learned from doing
some UX studies, which

00:26:50.180 --> 00:26:53.360
is autosaving.

00:26:53.360 --> 00:26:56.510
So we've sort of trained users
with a lot of these cloud apps

00:26:56.510 --> 00:27:00.390
now, particularly Google
Docs, that they should

00:27:00.390 --> 00:27:01.810
never have to hit save.

00:27:01.810 --> 00:27:04.090
They should just do their work
and things just magically

00:27:04.090 --> 00:27:09.180
happen and it's reliable, and
it's always up to date and

00:27:09.180 --> 00:27:11.920
always reliable.

00:27:11.920 --> 00:27:14.550
And just to show how much people
have learned to rely on

00:27:14.550 --> 00:27:17.940
this, that same UX study I
talked about earlier, 4/5 of

00:27:17.940 --> 00:27:21.640
the users didn't even think
about saving their files.

00:27:21.640 --> 00:27:23.430
They just assumed whatever they
typed in, whatever they

00:27:23.430 --> 00:27:28.100
did in all these apps that we
were testing, it just worked.

00:27:28.100 --> 00:27:30.520
You can imagine the
consequences, though, if your

00:27:30.520 --> 00:27:32.040
app doesn't actually do this.

00:27:32.040 --> 00:27:39.400
So I'm doing all my work, and
two hours later I closed my

00:27:39.400 --> 00:27:43.270
browser, I had to shut down or
something happens, and I'm

00:27:43.270 --> 00:27:45.705
sitting here thinking all my
content's safe and it's gone,

00:27:45.705 --> 00:27:47.980
it's vanished.

00:27:47.980 --> 00:27:51.200
So thinking about how to
do autosave in your

00:27:51.200 --> 00:27:53.291
applications--

00:27:53.291 --> 00:27:56.620
there are some complexities,
though.

00:27:56.620 --> 00:27:59.260
Who here attended the first
talk on Drive today?

00:27:59.260 --> 00:28:00.870
Anyone?

00:28:00.870 --> 00:28:02.950
So a handful of people.

00:28:02.950 --> 00:28:05.890
So there was something really
cool that was previewed in

00:28:05.890 --> 00:28:08.810
that talk, which is
collaboration API, which is

00:28:08.810 --> 00:28:12.920
basically operational transform
mutation-based API

00:28:12.920 --> 00:28:15.120
for doing collaboration.

00:28:15.120 --> 00:28:17.160
That's not something we have
ready yet, though, so when you

00:28:17.160 --> 00:28:20.320
deal with Drive, you have to
deal with Drive in the context

00:28:20.320 --> 00:28:22.570
of reading and writing blobs.

00:28:22.570 --> 00:28:25.520
And, of course, if you're going
to autosave, you have to

00:28:25.520 --> 00:28:27.650
make all these different
tradeoffs now.

00:28:27.650 --> 00:28:30.480
If I have a small file, saving
that file frequently isn't

00:28:30.480 --> 00:28:31.350
that big of a deal.

00:28:31.350 --> 00:28:33.780
But as the file size gets
bigger, it becomes more and

00:28:33.780 --> 00:28:37.260
more expensive for me to
do frequent savings.

00:28:37.260 --> 00:28:40.900
So we have to figure out how
much quota, how much bandwidth

00:28:40.900 --> 00:28:43.680
do I want to use, versus how
much risk do I want to expose

00:28:43.680 --> 00:28:46.710
that user to in case anything
were to go wrong.

00:28:46.710 --> 00:28:51.020
Likewise, the other aspect of
this is a feature of the Drive

00:28:51.020 --> 00:28:55.010
API, which is revisions.

00:28:55.010 --> 00:28:57.610
Anytime that you save content,
you have the choice of when to

00:28:57.610 --> 00:29:00.190
create new revision that the
user can go back and revert

00:29:00.190 --> 00:29:02.920
to, or whether or not you're
just going to touch the head.

00:29:02.920 --> 00:29:04.920
So when you're doing something
like autosaving, you have to

00:29:04.920 --> 00:29:09.800
think about what save events
are significant enough to

00:29:09.800 --> 00:29:12.220
cause a new revision versus
which ones you only wanted to

00:29:12.220 --> 00:29:16.250
show up as just an update
to the head revision.

00:29:16.250 --> 00:29:19.010
If I create a new revision on
every keystroke, it would

00:29:19.010 --> 00:29:21.780
basically render the revision
history useless.

00:29:21.780 --> 00:29:25.120
I'm not going to sit there and
try to reconstruct eight

00:29:25.120 --> 00:29:26.210
characters ago--

00:29:26.210 --> 00:29:29.330
it's just not something that
would be useful for a user.

00:29:29.330 --> 00:29:30.830
It turns out it's actually
not that hard to

00:29:30.830 --> 00:29:33.280
get this logic right.

00:29:33.280 --> 00:29:35.430
How you do this in your app
is going to be obviously

00:29:35.430 --> 00:29:38.240
particular to what you're
doing, but here's just a

00:29:38.240 --> 00:29:42.570
little JavaScript snippet that
I put together in a demo app.

00:29:42.570 --> 00:29:45.980
It turned out to actually work
pretty well, and it gave me

00:29:45.980 --> 00:29:51.110
what I felt as a user was close
to expected behavior and

00:29:51.110 --> 00:29:55.150
close to how our own
editors work.

00:29:55.150 --> 00:29:56.480
So in this case, all
I have here is

00:29:56.480 --> 00:29:57.460
really just two things.

00:29:57.460 --> 00:30:01.060
I have an autosaver, which in
this case is just going to be

00:30:01.060 --> 00:30:01.815
an interval function.

00:30:01.815 --> 00:30:04.880
It's going to run every
30 seconds.

00:30:04.880 --> 00:30:08.420
We can tune that either way
depending on our needs.

00:30:08.420 --> 00:30:11.280
It's just going to do a check if
the doc is dirty, I have a

00:30:11.280 --> 00:30:16.240
chance to save, I'm
going to save it.

00:30:16.240 --> 00:30:19.410
When it saves, it's going to
say, well, if the last time I

00:30:19.410 --> 00:30:21.910
saved this is really
long ago--

00:30:21.910 --> 00:30:26.075
maybe it's hours, maybe it's
days, it's time to create a

00:30:26.075 --> 00:30:26.740
new revision.

00:30:26.740 --> 00:30:29.330
But if I just saved it 30
seconds ago, I'm just going to

00:30:29.330 --> 00:30:31.790
consider that the same editing
session, and I'm just going to

00:30:31.790 --> 00:30:34.000
update the last copy.

00:30:34.000 --> 00:30:35.520
Likewise, we can have
an explicit save

00:30:35.520 --> 00:30:36.860
action in our menu.

00:30:36.860 --> 00:30:40.550
In that case, this is debatable,
but I decided if

00:30:40.550 --> 00:30:42.910
the user says I want to save
this document, I think that's

00:30:42.910 --> 00:30:46.460
important enough to create a
new revision in our thing.

00:30:46.460 --> 00:30:49.350
It actually turns out you can do
autosave with blobs that's

00:30:49.350 --> 00:30:54.360
fairly reliable and fairly
frequent with actually not

00:30:54.360 --> 00:30:56.040
that much code.

00:30:56.040 --> 00:30:59.320
So that's that.

00:30:59.320 --> 00:31:00.870
MIKE PROCOPIO: Great.

00:31:00.870 --> 00:31:03.160
So one of the features that we
announced this morning, when

00:31:03.160 --> 00:31:06.750
we went live announcing the
Google Drive SDK v2, is a new

00:31:06.750 --> 00:31:10.350
feature that lets third-party
apps operate directly on

00:31:10.350 --> 00:31:11.940
native Google Docs types.

00:31:11.940 --> 00:31:14.030
And this is important, because--
and I didn't get

00:31:14.030 --> 00:31:16.890
exact clearance on the number,
but something like eleventy

00:31:16.890 --> 00:31:20.240
gabillion files that are native
Google Docs types are

00:31:20.240 --> 00:31:20.390
stored in Drive.

00:31:20.390 --> 00:31:22.810
STEVEN BAZYL: That might be a
little bit of a stretch, but

00:31:22.810 --> 00:31:24.195
we'll get there.

00:31:24.195 --> 00:31:24.690
MIKE PROCOPIO: OK.

00:31:24.690 --> 00:31:25.470
We'll get there, you promise?

00:31:25.470 --> 00:31:25.760
STEVEN BAZYL: Yeah.

00:31:25.760 --> 00:31:26.580
Just give us--

00:31:26.580 --> 00:31:27.700
MIKE PROCOPIO: Eleventy
gabillion--

00:31:27.700 --> 00:31:30.090
that's a lot of native Google
Docs types, and there's no

00:31:30.090 --> 00:31:31.750
reason why third-party apps
shouldn't be able

00:31:31.750 --> 00:31:32.980
to operate on those.

00:31:32.980 --> 00:31:36.610
As it turns out, the data type
that's associated with, for

00:31:36.610 --> 00:31:40.510
example, Google Doc or a
presentation is Google

00:31:40.510 --> 00:31:41.440
proprietary.

00:31:41.440 --> 00:31:44.850
It's snapshot based, there's
some logging so we can do

00:31:44.850 --> 00:31:46.130
things like track revision.

00:31:46.130 --> 00:31:48.450
It's a fairly intricate data
model that we don't need to

00:31:48.450 --> 00:31:52.210
expose, but what we can do is
programmatically expose

00:31:52.210 --> 00:31:54.380
exportable snapshots, read-only

00:31:54.380 --> 00:31:56.660
representations of that file.

00:31:56.660 --> 00:32:00.440
So for example, what we can do
now is a Google document has

00:32:00.440 --> 00:32:02.810
the capacity to export as PDF.

00:32:02.810 --> 00:32:04.960
And do we have any apps
that can read PDFs?

00:32:04.960 --> 00:32:06.730
Sure we do-- e-readers,
faxing.

00:32:06.730 --> 00:32:09.920
So what that means is right now
from the Google Drive UI

00:32:09.920 --> 00:32:12.390
for apps that support it-- and
none do yet, because we just

00:32:12.390 --> 00:32:15.430
announced it this morning, but
this is coming imminently--

00:32:15.430 --> 00:32:17.780
you will be able to simply
right click on a Google

00:32:17.780 --> 00:32:21.040
document or presentation or
spreadsheet and open it with

00:32:21.040 --> 00:32:25.280
whatever apps can actually
handle the common export

00:32:25.280 --> 00:32:26.290
functionality.

00:32:26.290 --> 00:32:29.800
So in this case, a PDF for the
doc is able to be faxed.

00:32:29.800 --> 00:32:32.860
And another example is that
SlideRocket has the ability to

00:32:32.860 --> 00:32:35.920
read in Microsoft Office
presentations, PowerPoint

00:32:35.920 --> 00:32:40.570
presentations, and our built-in
presentations editor

00:32:40.570 --> 00:32:43.687
in the name of data liberation
has the capacity to export in

00:32:43.687 --> 00:32:44.290
that format.

00:32:44.290 --> 00:32:48.260
So we can actually import a
Google presentation directly

00:32:48.260 --> 00:32:50.380
into a third-party
app, SlideRocket.

00:32:50.380 --> 00:32:53.440
So that was announced today, and
we're very excited about

00:32:53.440 --> 00:32:56.990
that, and that will be rolling
out very soon.

00:32:56.990 --> 00:32:59.150
Example file formats that we
can support are, of course,

00:32:59.150 --> 00:33:00.580
the obvious one is PDFs.

00:33:00.580 --> 00:33:04.240
And there's a few that may not
be necessarily obvious at

00:33:04.240 --> 00:33:04.880
initial glance.

00:33:04.880 --> 00:33:07.400
But if you have a text editor,
there's no reason that a plain

00:33:07.400 --> 00:33:10.910
text editor shouldn't be able
to open a Google document.

00:33:10.910 --> 00:33:13.200
Meanwhile, if you have an image
editor, you should be

00:33:13.200 --> 00:33:17.670
able to read this vectorized
drawing format that we do with

00:33:17.670 --> 00:33:24.910
SVG or in a raster format
like a JPEG or PNG.

00:33:24.910 --> 00:33:26.600
To do this, it's very simple.

00:33:26.600 --> 00:33:30.790
You already in the Developer
APIs Console, you opt into

00:33:30.790 --> 00:33:33.400
certain types that your app has
the capability to open,

00:33:33.400 --> 00:33:36.970
and with the checking of this
box now, which is new, you

00:33:36.970 --> 00:33:39.260
will automatically be able to
do this, and it will be

00:33:39.260 --> 00:33:40.740
generally transparent to you.

00:33:40.740 --> 00:33:44.470
You'll just have to read from a
different place to actually

00:33:44.470 --> 00:33:47.290
get the data from the exportable
endpoint that we

00:33:47.290 --> 00:33:49.858
give you automatically.

00:33:49.858 --> 00:33:50.900
STEVEN BAZYL: Cool.

00:33:50.900 --> 00:33:51.920
Thanks.

00:33:51.920 --> 00:33:55.950
The last thing I want to talk
about is making your app

00:33:55.950 --> 00:33:56.940
discoverable.

00:33:56.940 --> 00:33:59.540
The reason we're all building
these apps--

00:33:59.540 --> 00:34:02.460
not all of us-- but we want to
get users, we want to get

00:34:02.460 --> 00:34:05.330
customers, we want them to use
our app, be productive, and

00:34:05.330 --> 00:34:08.370
hopefully turn into
paying customers.

00:34:08.370 --> 00:34:10.050
And they only do that if
they can find our app

00:34:10.050 --> 00:34:12.820
in the first place.

00:34:12.820 --> 00:34:15.929
For Drive, we do use the Chrome
Web Store as a way for

00:34:15.929 --> 00:34:19.199
people to discover applications
that work with

00:34:19.199 --> 00:34:20.730
Google Drive.

00:34:20.730 --> 00:34:22.120
So, obviously, it's very
important to make sure you

00:34:22.120 --> 00:34:24.780
have a really strong
presence there.

00:34:24.780 --> 00:34:26.139
Actually, we can
even just go--

00:34:26.139 --> 00:34:31.300
I think as of yesterday we just
added a new collection so

00:34:31.300 --> 00:34:33.239
people can find apps.

00:34:33.239 --> 00:34:35.840
And, of course, everyone gets
this nice little "works with

00:34:35.840 --> 00:34:38.070
Drive" badge on their
listings.

00:34:38.070 --> 00:34:39.280
MIKE PROCOPIO: Look at all
those pretty apps.

00:34:39.280 --> 00:34:41.020
STEVEN BAZYL: I know, these
are awesome apps.

00:34:41.020 --> 00:34:44.670
And you can see the importance
of having a fairly nice

00:34:44.670 --> 00:34:46.000
presence versus--

00:34:46.000 --> 00:34:50.380
not to point out any really bad
apps-- but if you don't do

00:34:50.380 --> 00:34:53.179
a good job, you get down to the
bottom and nobody's going

00:34:53.179 --> 00:34:53.989
to find your app.

00:34:53.989 --> 00:34:56.480
So you really want to focus on
making sure you have a nice,

00:34:56.480 --> 00:34:58.190
clean presence.

00:34:58.190 --> 00:35:00.600
These are actually reviewed by
humans, the images and the

00:35:00.600 --> 00:35:03.500
assets, and there are certain
guidelines that you have to

00:35:03.500 --> 00:35:07.020
hit, particularly if you want
to get into any of the large

00:35:07.020 --> 00:35:09.220
banners on the Chrome
Web Store.

00:35:09.220 --> 00:35:11.360
So I would encourage you to
check out the documentation

00:35:11.360 --> 00:35:14.810
for Chrome Web Store for how
to publish apps, and pay

00:35:14.810 --> 00:35:16.900
